  <result type="1">
   <title>
    <narrative xml:lang="EN">1.4 HRDs have access to all major ISHR publications in a variety of languages, distributed in diverse, accessible formats.</narrative>
   </title>
   <reference code="266293" vocabulary="99"></reference>
   <indicator aggregation-status="0" ascending="0" measure="1">
    <title>
     <narrative xml:lang="EN">1.4 HRDs have access to all major ISHR publications in a variety of languages, distributed in diverse, accessible formats.

- Number of ISHR publications produced during the year
- Level of dissemination (e.g. N&#xB0; of copies printed, N&#xB0; of online downloads)
- N&#xB0; of languages in which publications are available
- Qualitative level of the publications</narrative>
    </title>
    <period>
     <period-start iso-date="2018-01-01"></period-start>
     <period-end iso-date="2018-12-31"></period-end>
     <target value="TBD"></target>
     <actual value="1.4. ISHR released at least 2 practical manuals in 2017:
HRD guide to Third Committee (NY) &#x2013; provided HRDs with comprehensive and practical guidance to engage with Third Committee of the GA. available in English. Spanish and French.
Updated guide to NGO Committee (NY) &#x2013; provided HRDs with updated. practical guide to obtaining accreditation with UN. available in English. Spanish. French and Arabic.
The publications were distributed in hard copies to 93 and 221 ppl respectively. Soft copies were sent to more than 7.000 publication subscribers and there have been additionally 380 and 200 (respectively) unique downloads for each of the two publications from our webpage.
Reprisals handbook near final by May 2018"></actual>
    </period>
   </indicator>
  </result>
  <result type="1">
   <title>
    <narrative xml:lang="EN">1.7 With and through ISHR, HRDs and their organisations have access to expert pro bono legal support to submit complaints and communications to international and regional mechanisms to pursue justice and accountability for restrictions and violations agai</narrative>
   </title>
   <reference code="266292" vocabulary="99"></reference>
   <indicator aggregation-status="0" ascending="0" measure="1">
    <title>
     <narrative xml:lang="EN">N&#xB0; of submissions &amp; reports produced by ISHR &amp; national partners
Proportion of ISHR submissions made with HRDs

- N&#xB0; of complaints made to HR mechanisms
- N&#xB0; of studies and initial assessments carried out with a view to consider a formal complaint</narrative>
    </title>
    <period>
     <period-start iso-date="2018-01-01"></period-start>
     <period-end iso-date="2018-12-31"></period-end>
     <target value="1.7 At least two cases per year will be litigated by ISHR. with the support of internationally renowned pro bono lawyers. for a total of eight cases by 2020 with the treaty bodies. special procedures and regional mechanisms"></target>
     <actual value="1.7. During the reporting period ISHR initiated proceedings for a complaint to CEDAW on the case of a prominent HRD in Thailand. We also initiated and led a joint open NGO letter for treaty bodies to make better use of protective measures in cases of reprisals against complainants
In 2018 alone. to date. ISHR submitted 6 communications on reprisals to UN human rights bodies"></actual>
    </period>
   </indicator>
  </result>
